ladders.explanation:
The core logic of the brute force approach is systematically examining every possible pair of elements in the array and accumulating their GCDs. The intuition is that to compute the total sum of GCDs for all pairs, we must consider each pair exactly once. The algorithm uses nested loops: the outer loop iterates through each element as the first element of a pair, and the inner loop iterates through elements starting from the current outer index to avoid redundant computations (if we consider i≤j). For each pair (arr[i], arr[j]), we compute the GCD using the Euclidean algorithm and add it to a running total. The key insight is that we need O(n²) GCD computations for an array of size n. This connects to the full problem as the main computational structure. Common mistakes include: 1) Off-by-one errors in loop boundaries, 2) Double-counting pairs if not careful with indices, 3) Forgetting to handle self-pairs (i=j). The real code pattern is nested for-loops with i from 0 to n-1 and j from i to n-1.

Pseudocode:
function pairwise_gcd_sum(arr):
    n = len(arr)
    total = 0
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(i, n):
            total += gcd(arr[i], arr[j])
    return total

This building block focuses on generating all unique pairs of indices where i≤j, which is essential for the pairwise computations. The intuition is that we need to consider each pair exactly once without duplication. The algorithm uses two nested loops: the outer loop variable i goes from 0 to n-1, and for each i, the inner loop variable j goes from i to n-1. This ensures that we get all combinations where the first index is less than or equal to the second index, covering self-pairs (i=j) and distinct pairs (i<j) without repetition. The total number of pairs generated is n(n+1)/2 (triangular number). This connects to the core logic by providing the pair generation mechanism. Common mistakes include: 1) Starting j from 0 (which would double-count pairs), 2) Using i<j instead of i≤j (missing self-pairs), 3) Incorrect loop boundaries causing index errors. The real code pattern is straightforward nested for-loops.

Pseudocode:
function generate_pairs(n):
    pairs = []
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(i, n):
            pairs.append((i, j))
    return pairs
